author: @Tapajara
text: Python is a very bad programming language in so many ways. I think that beginners who really want to know how computers work should certainly not start to learn programming with this terrible language because it will ruin their perceptions of how computers actually work. The C language requires you to conform your thinking to how the computer works. Python, on the other hand, tries to guess at what you mean and generates the code that does what it thinks you want to happen. And it burns up 99% of your computer's power in doing this guess work.

text: Your videos are exceptional. I enjoy them all. In this one it would help to expand a little on when to use "is" or ==. "Value is True" seems to work, but I don't trust it based upon your description about having identical memory locations. author: @delapuenteignacio
text: One thing that might be worth adding is that if I define two integers rather than lists, then they both get stored in the same memory location. i.e. x =  3 y = 3  "x is y" outputsTrue. This won't happen with strings unless its just one word. So if x = 'a string' y = 'a string' "x is y" outputs False but if x = 'justoneword' y = 'justoneword' "x is y" outputs True.   Go figure...
